  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Very unhelpful and rude staff! PALS &amp;amp; General Office &lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I have been treated in both A&amp;amp;E and the UCC three times since a road traffic accident six days ago.
First responder from NWAS at the scene - lovely. 
Reception ladies when checking into A&amp;amp;E and also UCC, lovely and helpful and provided me with tissues as I was upset.
Triage nurses - lovely. 
UCC Dr (saw twice) and A&amp;amp;E Dr - lovely. 
X-Ray Staff - lovely 
Admin Manager - absolute lack of understanding for my situation and lack of empathy. No solutions or help/advice given.  Felt like I was fighting a losing battle when speaking with her. It was very frustrating so I went to PALS for support and advice.  The response that I got from the lady at PALS was cold, uncaring, unhelpful, a total lack of empathy, a total lack of compassion, a total lack of customer service. I came away and was upset for the whole day. I am still upset now. I would not go to them for support again.  
I am going to make an official complaint today to more senior members of staff about the conduct of the General Office Manager and the lady at PALS.  I should actually be resting and recuperating! 
I also had an appointment with an ENT Specialist yesterday morning where I was told that I had a brain tumour so the last thing I needed was to be treated in such a way and ‘talked down to’.  I was on my own with my little girl and even she said that the two women were both rude and unhelpful. My daughter is eleven. 
ENT Receptionist - lovely
ENT Dr and Nurse - lovely and lovely 
ENT Medical Trainee - lovely 
Audiologist - lovely 
I spoke to an ENT Medical Secretary on the phone following my appt - lovely
RPH Switchboard Operator - lovely 

The two people that I have issues with showed signs of being on a ‘power trip’.  I would not recruit them to work for my company or any of my clients (I am a recruiter with over 25 years experience). I would not employ them to work  in an environment where patients need support, empathy, compassion and understanding.  

Such a shame to have this experience when most of the other people who I have come into contact with this week at RPH have been lovely. &lt;/CommentText&gt;
